[recv] {"type": "turn_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Evaluating resource handling in testing**\n\nI’m trying to understand how metadata works with ResourceBundle.getBundle. It seems like if I’m compiling for native, I might need a resource config if it’s external. The Graal TCK probably runs an agent that merges generated metadata. The user mentioned that Forge manages metadata generation externally, but I need to add a test without resources. I’m worried about a MissingResourceException if resource configuration isn’t there during the native compile. Perhaps I should also test calling the public API with built-in Java resources.\n\n**Considering resource bundle creation**\n\nI’m exploring how to make a resource bundle available in a JDK native image, like sun.text.resources. There’s a thought that native image localization could be an issue. I’m thinking it might be better to create test resource properties directly. But I'm unsure if I should place these in src/test/resources or follow the guideline to update only under the resolved target test source root. Using a class-based ListResourceBundle that’s nested in the test Java class could work, but I’m worried about the restriction on class visibility and necessary metadata for the native image.\n\n**Exploring resource bundle options**\n\nI’m considering whether adding a second class as a top-level package-private option is okay. It might be better to create a properties file for this. Regarding native resource bundles, if I add a test resource, I wonder if the Gradle plugin will auto-configure all test resources. I also need to take a look at the existing resource tests to understand how they are set up and make sure everything is aligned properly.", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_0f25f6128600ab5a016a1184f9659c819387f33a39d5e0967c\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAABqEYUEnhmTswNN7gJd44TOpHFhMeW0qJvQ_TpcKMSne3EDfwu3s6MfnHiChBGXB4P09iUkJ